{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609860"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:52:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:52:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16130"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16130"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.17,0.14,0.41,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74603"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8821"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60097"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10135"},{"type":"tags","id":"12220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21046"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74603"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EComplete androgen insensitivity syndrome (CAIS) is a condition affecting individuals with a 46,XY karyotype, where the body is unable to respond to androgens. This results in the development of female external genitalia despite the presence of testes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the development of secondary sexual characteristics in complete androgen insensitivity syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Minimal breast development due to testosterone resistance","Normal breast development from testosterone aromatisation","Male pattern hair growth with gynaecomastia","Female pattern hair growth with clitoromegaly","Delayed puberty with primary amenorrhoea"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPeople with complete androgen insensitivity syndrome develop \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal breast development from testosterone aromatisation\u003C/strong\u003E. Their testes produce testosterone, but due to non-functional androgen receptors, this testosterone cannot exert its usual effects. Instead, the testosterone is converted peripherally to oestrogen by the enzyme aromatase, resulting in feminisation and breast development during puberty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other features described are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinimal breast development due to testosterone resistance\u003C/strong\u003E would not occur since breast tissue responds to oestrogen, not androgens\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMale pattern hair growth with gynaecomastia\u003C/strong\u003E is impossible because androgen-dependent body hair patterns cannot develop without functional androgen receptors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemale pattern hair growth with clitoromegaly\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as clitoral enlargement requires androgen action\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed puberty with primary amenorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E is partially incorrect - while amenorrhoea is present (due to absence of uterus), puberty occurs at the normal time\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of functional aromatase enzyme ensures normal female breast development despite the inability to respond to androgens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Complete androgen insensitivity syndrome (CAIS) is caused by mutations in the androgen receptor gene, leading to a lack of response to androgens.","Individuals with CAIS have a 46,XY karyotype but develop female external genitalia due to the inability to respond to androgens.","Breast development in CAIS occurs due to the aromatisation of testosterone to oestrogen."],"references":["Oakes MB, Eyvazzadeh AD, Quint E, Smith YR. Complete androgen insensitivity syndrome--a review. J Pediatr Adolesc Gynecol. 2008 Dec;21(6):305-10. doi: 10.1016/j.jpag.2007.09.006. PMID: 19064222.","Pizzo A, Lagan\u00e0 AS, Borrielli I, Dugo N. Complete androgen insensitivity syndrome: a rare case of disorder of sex development. Case Rep Obstet Gynecol. 2013;2013:232696. doi: 10.1155/2013/232696. Epub 2013 Feb 27. PMID: 23533861; PMCID: PMC3600229.","Batista RL, Costa EMF, Rodrigues AS, Gomes NL, Faria JA Jr, Nishi MY, Arnhold IJP, Domenice S, Mendonca BB. Androgen insensitivity syndrome: a review. Arch Endocrinol Metab. 2018 Mar-Apr;62(2):227-235. doi: 10.20945/2359-3997000000031. PMID: 29768628; PMCID: PMC10118986."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60097"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16130"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60097"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T19:41:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T19:42:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8821"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74603"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":